Course Description:
The Advanced Diploma in Critical Care Nursing aims to:
(a) improve the standard care provided to critically ill patients and their families;
(b) facilitate early and accurate diagnostic assessment;
(c) advance the science of critical care nursing; and
(d) support research initiatives.

Upon completion of the module, participants will be able to:
1. Relate analytics results with business value in healthcare sector;
2. Understand the key elements to build a successful healthcare analytics solution;
3. Understand data source, data collection, data cleansing in healthcare analytics;
4. Understand the key problems and challenges in healthcare clinical analytics area;
5. Master the common analytics techniques used in healthcare analytics, and be able to select the right techniques for different healthcare
analytics problems.
6. Understand the state-of-the-arts in healthcare analytics

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will be able to: 
• discuss the changing demographic and health care trends in Singapore; 
• explore evidence-based research in relation to healthcare and examine various research utilization models for application in clinical practice; 
• identify various type of healthcare services and financial system available in supporting the needs of patients with chronic conditions; 
• describe the theoretical knowledge of advanced pathophysiology related to chronic diseases and clinical management; 
• discuss the therapeutic effects and adverse effects of the drug; and use of counselling skills to educate patients on compliance to medications; 
• obtain a comprehensive history taking and physical examination with the correct technique and to interpret any abnormal clinical results and physical signs presented by the patients; 
• apply health teaching strategies to educate patients to self-manage their chronic 
• conditions and minimize long- term complications; 
• apply motivational interviewing strategies and techniques to facilitate and engage intrinsic motivation within the patients and/or their families in order to elicit sustainable behaviour change; 
• incorporate the nursing and case management processes to coordinate care and recognise how to access and utilise resources and networks to meet patient/family needs; 
• demonstrate understanding of the principles of rehabilitation to achieve maximum functional independence for the patients; 
• demonstrate understanding of the goals and principles that underpin the concept of palliative care nursing; and 
• describe the physical, psychological, social and spiritual issues of patients in palliative care for those with non-cancer organ failures.

