Upon successful completion of the course, the students will be able to:
• utilize critical thinking and clinical reasoning to identify problems and develop care plans;
• assess health education needs and conduct focused patient/ family education;
• support evidence-based practice to improve the standard of care provided to the surgical patients; and 
• display confidence in their clinical abilities and have a strong commitment to quality patient care and continuing education.

The SDCO aims to prepare students to: 
• Demonstrate understanding of Singapore’s ageing problem and its impact on the older
population’s vision or ocular health, and able to assess and manage visually impaired
patients; 
• Demonstrate advance level of critical &amp; analytical thinking so as to accurately diagnose common age-related eye diseases; 
• Exercise clinical judgement in determining the necessity of a referral or monitoring for patients with age-related eye disease; 
• Demonstrate competency in monitoring stable eye diseases, with the ability to recognise the need to refer for medical attention; 
• Demonstrate proficient knowledge and skills to implement refractive correction strategies that can be employed by both optometrists and ophthalmologists; 
• Manage patients with myopia, as well as those with myopic-related complications proficiently

On completion of the course, the learners should be able to:
• identify common problems in the mother and infant after delivery;
• demonstrate competence in the basic care of mother and infant;
• provide support, care and/or health teaching to the breastfeeding mother and infant;
• handle the infant safely; 
• initiate first aid care immediately after an injury; and
• communicate effectively with the mother and family members through the use of verbal and/or non-verbal channels.

On completion of the module, the students should be able to:
1. justify the decision to perform myopia management in adults, young adults or young children; 
2. manage adverse outcomes, such as variable and poor vision in children using the different treatment strategies (multifocal contact lenses, orthokeratology, low-dose atropine); 
3. diagnose and manage the signs and symptoms of pathology associated with high myopia; and
4. explain and discuss with children and parents likely myopia control outcomes, pros and cons of different management strategies, including behavioural, optical and therapeutic options.

On completion of the module, the students should be able to:
advanced knowledge and skills in assessing and detecting common eye diseases in the community; 
relate the impact of common systemic diseases on patient’s overall well-being and ocular health;
interpret the results of advanced diagnostic tests;
develop the most appropriate management plan through information integration (such as patient presentation, clinical test results); and
communicate effectively (written and oral) with patients and healthcare professionals.

The objectives of this Part-Time Diploma are to enable students to:
- Coordinate and navigate care of clients in order to ensure seamless transition of care;
- Coordinate all aspects of discharge planning;
- Act as a liaison between patients, family members and the multidisciplinary team (MDT), institutions, external agencies, and the community;
- Work with community partners to support patients in achieving individual health improvement;
- Connect individuals with appropriate health and social services to make best use of community resources to tackle health issues.
- Assist individuals to change their health behavior to improve their own health and wellbeing;
- Promote health in the community through the application of behaviour change strategies; and 
- Conduct and evaluate appropriate screenings for the community to establish health and fitness assessments.

•	Apply the principles of integrated care to assess patients for biopsychosocial, nursing and financial needs in inpatient and outpatient settings;
•	Develop comprehensive care plans to effectively utilise community resources for care coordination and co-manage patients with chronic diseases in the community; 
•	Apply the principles of palliative care in advance care planning;
•	Demonstrate effective communication and motivational interviewing skills to modify clients’ behaviours and lifestyles;
•	Provide education to patients/ families, and/or caregivers on:
chronic disease management/ mental health issues/ coping strategies
•	Recommend appropriate financial schemes for patients; 
•	Assist seniors with generic home exercises;
•	Demonstrate applied critical thinking and problem solving using leadership and management principles and strategies in the delivery of patient care;
•	Identify and discuss the various types of information systems, devices, and applications used in the delivery of health services;
•	Evaluate optimal utilisation of resources, efficiency in the delivery of high-quality care, patient flow, capacity management and other clinical cost reduction initiatives;
•	Identify and discuss common social issues relating to the well-being of children, youth, and families.

At the end of the course, learners will be able to:
•	recognise the roles and responsibilities of other health and social worker in institutions and community;
•	identify the values and professional ethics of the multi-professional team;
•	demonstrate effective communication to facilitate information, respecting one and another’s perspectives to improve patient/clients outcome;
•	apply inter-professional facilitation skills to facilitate and collaborate inter-professional team discussions to achieve team goals.

