Chronic diseases are long-term medical conditions that are generally progressive. Statistics show that Singapore’s ageing population and adoption of unhealthy lifestyles have contributed to the increasing prevalence of chronic diseases. This course is designed for healthcare professional caring for patients with chronic diseases in the community setting. 

Learning Outcomes
At the end of the course, participants should be able to:

1. identify drivers and challenges shaping the healthcare environment;
2. explain  characteristics of common chronic diseases;
3. describe the clinical manifestations, medical, nursing and pharmacological management of common chronic diseases;
4. discuss self-management strategies for clients with common chronic diseases;
5. describe available support for clients with common chronic diseases and their carers;
6. apply motivational interviewing skills when interacting with clients;
7. apply effective strategies in health education and health promotion; and
8. recognise the importance of empowering patients to self-manage chronic conditions.

Upon completion of the course, the participant will be able to:

1. Monitor and manage clinical outcomes in inpatient, ambulatory and public health settings;

2. Monitor and manage performance of healthcare institutions and patient satisfaction;

3. Develop structural, process and outcome indicators; and

4. Carry out quality improvement and patient safety programmes in healthcare organisations on a sustained basis

Learners will be able to: 
1. understand common women’s and reproductive health issues in Singapore;
2. recognize women’s health concerns and provide appropriate advice or referrals; 
3. analyse physiological, psychological, sociological, and cultural aspects which may influence women and reproductive health. 
4. demonstrate evidence-based and policy informed practice to promote women’s and reproductive health; 
5. provide health education to empower women at different stages of life. 
6. advocate health and wellness among women holistically; and
7. adopt culturally appropriate care for women and reproductive health

